</h3><p class="sc-kHOZwM oQMan pf-21_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Splinters—fragments of wood, metal, glass, or plastic that penetrate the skin—can cause discomfort and, if left untreated, infections. The Health and Safety Executive (HSE) does not provide specific guidance on splinters but underscores the importance of general wound care and first aid in the workplace. Quick and appropriate action is necessary to prevent complications, aligning with broader health and safety protocols.
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-iqseJM ducrfW pf-23_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fHeRUh cCunWv pf-24_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-bTfYFJ fFWOZc pf-25_ pf-heading-1-h3">Key definitions</h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-kYHfwS lkFAWj pf-27_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-28_ pf-text-1"><strong>Splinter</strong> - A foreign body that penetrates the skin, potentially causing injury or infection.







</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-30_ pf-text-1"><strong>Infection </strong>- The invasion and multiplication of microorganisms such as bacteria, viruses, and parasites that are not normally present within the body.






</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-iqseJM ducrfW pf-32_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fHeRUh cCunWv pf-33_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-bTfYFJ fFWOZc pf-34_ pf-heading-1-h3">Relevant legislation and regulations</h3><p class="sc-kHOZwM oQMan pf-36_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">In the UK, the Health and Safety (First-Aid) Regulations 1981 require employers to provide adequate and appropriate equipment, facilities, and personnel to ensure employees receive immediate attention if they are injured or taken ill at work. This includes managing minor injuries such as splinters.<br>

</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-iqseJM ducrfW pf-38_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fHeRUh cCunWv pf-39_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-bTfYFJ fFWOZc pf-40_ pf-heading-1-h3">Best practices for splinter removal</h3><p class="sc-kHOZwM oQMan pf-42_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">According to NHS guidelines and the British Red Cross, the recommended steps for removing a splinter are:<br>

</p><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-kYHfwS lkFAWj pf-44_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-45_ pf-text-1"><strong>Clean the area </strong>- Before attempting to remove the splinter, clean the skin with soap and water to reduce the risk of infection.






</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-47_ pf-text-1"><strong>Use tweezers </strong>- Sterilise tweezers with rubbing alcohol. Gently pull the splinter out in the same direction it entered.








</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-49_ pf-text-1"><strong>Clean and protect </strong>- After removal, clean the wound again and apply a plaster or bandage to keep it clean.









</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-xiLah hUMvDY pf-51_ pf-text-1"><strong>Elevate the affected area</strong> - This can help reduce swelling and discomfort.









</li></ul><p class="sc-kHOZwM oQMan pf-53_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Employers should ensure that all first aid kits are equipped with sterilised tweezers and antiseptic wipes or solutions, as part of compliance with workplace health and safety standards.<br>

</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-iqseJM ducrfW pf-55_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fHeRUh cCunWv pf-56_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-bTfYFJ fFWOZc pf-57_ pf-heading-1-h3">Handling complications</h3><p class="sc-kHOZwM oQMan pf-59_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">If a splinter is deeply embedded, or if removal attempts fail, it is important to seek medical attention. Signs of infection, such as redness, swelling, or pus, also necessitate professional care.<br>

</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-iqseJM ducrfW pf-61_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fHeRUh cCunWv pf-62_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-bTfYFJ fFWOZc pf-63_ pf-heading-1-h3">Recommendations for training and preparedness
